          "body": "The promise of 4:5-6 is the most directly Messianic statement in the closing chapter. God will send 'Elijah the prophet before the coming of the great and terrible day of the LORD.' The mission is explicitly heart-restoration: turning the hearts of fathers to children and children to fathers — a re-knitting of the relational fabric that sin has torn across generations. Jesus explicitly identifies John the Baptist as the fulfillment of this promise (Matthew 11:14; 17:12), and the angel Gabriel announces John's birth using Malachi 4:6's language directly (Luke 1:17). Orthodox interpretation presents a genuine tension here: if John the Baptist is the promised Elijah, is the 'great and terrible Day' his contemporaries' generation — fulfilled in AD 70 — or does John fulfill the Elijah-role provisionally, with the Day still awaiting its final eschatological fullness at the return of Christ? Premillennial interpreters (Swindoll, Pentecost) read a future fulfillment still outstanding; amillennial interpreters (Beale, Kim) see the inauguration in Christ's first advent with ongoing fulfillment in the church age. Both positions are held by orthodox scholars; what neither disputes is that John the Baptist is Malachi's Elijah and that the Day is Jesus Christ's to execute."
