          "title": "Cherem — the last word and the gospel's answer",
          "body": "The Hebrew Old Testament ends with the word *cherem*: total ban, utter destruction, the most severe covenant sanction available. 'Lest I come and smite the land with a curse' (4:6). The conditional is not idle threat — the same word (*cherem*) was used for Canaanite cities given over to holy-war destruction (Joshua 6:17), and Deuteronomy 28-29 invoked it as the ultimate sanction for covenant apostasy. The canon ends not with resolution but with urgency: the Elijah-ministry must succeed or the ultimate curse falls. The New Testament takes this word with full seriousness. Galatians 3:13 announces that Christ redeemed us from the curse (*katara*) of the law by becoming a curse for us. The *cherem* that Malachi 4:6 threatens as the alternative to restoration is the curse that the Son of God absorbed at Golgotha. The last word of the Old Testament is answered by the central act of the New. Between the last page of Malachi and the first page of Matthew, four centuries pass — and then a voice cries in the wilderness."
