        "excerpt": "Remember the law of Moses My servant, even the statutes and ordinances which I commanded him in Horeb for all Israel.",
        "body": "After two verses of eschatological vision, verse 4 turns abruptly to the present with a single imperative: *zakhar* — remember. The verb is more than cognitive recall; in Hebrew covenant usage, *zakhar* implies active, obedient response. To remember the law of Moses is to live by it, not merely to recite it.\n\nThe choice of Moses and Horeb is deliberate and comprehensive. 'Moses My servant' is the covenant title used throughout Deuteronomy — the mediator of the Sinai covenant. 'Statutes and ordinances' (*choq* and *mishpat*) are the two main categories of Mosaic legislation, covering both the cultic regulations and the civil judgments. 'For all Israel' is not merely inclusive but covenantal — this law was not given to an elite class but to the whole community. The command 'remember' addressed to the post-exilic community means: in the interval between now and the coming Day, your mandate has not changed. No prophetic expectation of future transformation suspends present covenant fidelity.\n\nThis verse also performs a canonical function. It grounds eschatological hope in Torah-rooted identity. The community that waits for the Day of the Lord is not a community in suspension — it is Israel, constituted at Horeb, living by statutes and judgments given there. The Elijah-figure who will come (4:5-6) does not replace this Torah; he will call people back to the relational reality the Torah was designed to form. The Sermon on the Mount will make this relationship explicit: 'Do not think that I came to abolish the Law or the Prophets; I did not come to abolish but to fulfill' (Matthew 5:17).\n\nFor the book of Malachi as a whole, this verse is also a self-commentary. Malachi has spent four chapters pressing the covenant obligations of Torah — proper sacrifice (1:6-14), the teaching role of the priest (2:1-9), covenant marriage (2:14-16), tithes and offerings (3:10). 'Remember the law of Moses' is not a new command; it is the summary of everything Malachi has been saying."
